-- Ayala,  Gigastorage, Hyundai, Korea Electric: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview
-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 2010-09-29T21:45:18Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-29/ayala-gigastorage-hyundai-korea-electric-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in  Asian trading , excluding Japan. Stock
symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Ayala Land Inc.  (ALI PM): The largest Philippine builder
formed its real-estate investment trust unit AyalaLand
Commercial REIT Inc. to invest in shopping centers and offices
owned by the company, a stock-exchange filing showed. The unit
will eventually hold an initial share sale and buy assets to
increase its portfolio, it said. The stock increased 0.7 percent
to 17.70 pesos.  Gigastorage Corp.  (2406 TT): The Taiwanese maker of compact
discs said its board of directors approved a plan to invest as
much as NT$750 million to build plants to produce solar-cell
wafers. The investment will come from its own funds and
syndicated loans, according to the statement to the Taiwan stock
exchange. The shares added 0.3 percent to NT$48.75.  Hyundai Motor Co.  (005380 KS): South Korea’s largest
automaker plans to sell 5.5-year dollar bonds at a spread that’s
in the high 200 basis point range above similar-maturity U.S.
Treasuries, according to a person familiar with the matter, who
asked not to be identified as details are private. Hyundai
dropped 2.9 percent to 152,000 won.  Kencana Petroleum Bhd.  (KEPB MK): The Malaysian oil and gas
services provider said profit in the fourth quarter ended July
31 rose 37 percent from a year earlier to 41.5 million ringgit
($13.5 million) as revenue gained. Kencana was unchanged at 1.66
ringgit.  Korea Electric Power Corp.  (015760 KS): South Korea’s
biggest electricity producer agreed to buy a stake in a
Philippine power plant from BG Group Plc for $400 million. Korea
Electric beat other global companies to acquire the 40 percent
stake, the Seoul-based utility said in an e-mailed statement.
The shares fell 0.3 percent to 29,750 won.  Rizal Commercial Banking Corp.  (RCB PM): The bank may raise
$100 million from the sale of as many as 200 million shares in
the first quarter of 2011, a stock-exchange filing showed. Rizal
Bank will use the proceeds to expand its assets, for investment
and to fund “planned acquisitions of medium-sized banks,” it
said. The stock increased 0.2 percent to 28.30 pesos.  Thakral Holdings Group  (THG AU): The Australian property
management unit has appointed Jones Lang LaSalle and McVay Real
Estate to manage the sale of the Oasis Shopping Centre and the
Sofitel Gold Coast Broadbeach hotel. Thakral dropped 1.2 percent
to 43 Australian cents.  Zelan Bhd.  (ZELN MK): The Malaysian construction company
said it sold 4.2 million shares of IJM Corp. (IJM MK) for 21.7
million ringgit or at an average price of 5.12 ringgit a share.
Zelan added 1.5 percent to 68 sen. IJM rose 0.6 percent to 5.15
ringgit.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Anuchit Nguyen  in Bangkok at 
